I"½<p>Use nesting to form a hierarchy that expresses that one element contains or determines the following elements.</p>

<div class="grid-2">
<div>
    <p>This hierarchy is often used to indicate that some elements are only relevant if a given parent element is selected.</p>

    <p>The most common forms to express this dependency are to:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><a href="#disable-nested-elements">disable nested elements</a></li>
      <li><a href="#hide-nested-elements">hide nested elements</a></li>
    </ul>
  </div>
<div>
    <p><img src="../images/inactive/inactive-do.svg" alt="Example of an inactive checkbox inside an active checkbox" /></p>

    <figcaption>Example of a disabled nested element</figcaption>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 id="disable-nested-elements">Disable Nested Elements</h2>

<div class="grid-2">
<div>
    <iframe height="180" src="/photon/interactives/patterns/nesting/disable-hide-state_example.html" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" frameborder="0"></iframe>

    <figcaption>Interactive Example for disabled sub elements in a set of checkboxes</figcaption>
  </div>
<div>
    <p>Disable nested elements to help anticipate what enabling the parent will unlock, and to give additional context to the functionality of the parent.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 id="hide-nested-elements">Hide Nested Elements</h2>

<div class="grid-2">
<div>
    <iframe height="180" src="/photon/interactives/patterns/nesting/hide-sub_example.html" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" frameborder="0"></iframe>

    <figcaption>Interactive Example for hiding sub elements in a set of checkboxes</figcaption>
  </div>
<div>
    <p>Hide the nested elements if showing them would overly complicate the interface, or occupy too much space in the UI.</p>

    <p>Only use this if the visible part provides enough context for people to not be suprised by the additional content. Consider using sub-menues for hiding more information.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 id="usage-examples">Usage Examples</h2>

<h3 id="checkboxes">Checkboxes</h3>

<p>On Desktop checkboxes are often used in nested groups that disable parts of the options.</p>

<video controls="" loop="">
  <source src="../images/patterns/nesting/nesting_example_fx_pref_disable.mp4" type="video/mp4" />

![Example of disabled sub options in Firefox Preferences](../images/patterns/nesting/nesting_example_fx_pref_disable.gif)
</video>

<h3 id="drop-down-lists">Drop-down Lists</h3>

<p>Like Checkboxes, Drop-down lists can be used to determine what content to show. In this case content stays hidden until the corresponding list entry is selected.</p>

<video controls="" loop="">
  <source src="../images/patterns/nesting/nesting_example_fx_pref_hide.mp4" type="video/mp4" />

![Example of hidding sub options in Firefox Preferences](../images/patterns/nesting/nesting_example_fx_pref_hide.gif)
</video>

<h3 id="buttons-">Buttons <!-- should be it's own pattern menu --></h3>

<p>In a way, many buttons, like menus, also use nesting to hide content until pressed.</p>

<video controls="" loop="">
  <source src="../images/patterns/nesting/nesting_example_fx_button.mp4" type="video/mp4" />

![Example of hidding sub options with a button](../images/patterns/nesting/nesting_example_fx_button.gif)
</video>
